SIMPLE: honorable
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Honorable
<hw>Hon"or*a*ble</hw> <pr>(⟦ocr⟧n"⟦etil⟧r*⟦adot⟧*b'l)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>honorable</ets>, L.
<ets>honorabilis</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Worthy of honor; fit to
be esteemed or regarded; estimable; illustrious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy name and <qex>honorable</qex> family.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>High-minded; actuated by principles of honor, or a
scrupulous regard to probity, rectitude, or reputation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Proceeding from an upright and laudable cause, or
directed to a just and proper end; not base; irreproachable; fair;
<as>as, an <ex>honorable</ex> motive</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Is this proceeding just and <qex>honorable</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Conferring honor, or produced by noble
deeds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Honorable</qex> wounds from battle brought.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Worthy of respect; regarded with esteem; to be
commended; consistent with honor or rectitude.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Marriage is <qex>honorable</qex> in all.</q> <rj><qau>Heb. xiii.
4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Performed or accompanied with marks of honor, or
with testimonies of esteem; <as>as, an <ex>honorable</ex>
burial</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Of reputable association or use;
respectable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let her descend: my chambers are <qex>honorable</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>An epithet of respect or distinction; <as>as, the
<ex>honorable</ex> Senate; the <ex>honorable</ex>
gentleman.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Honorable</xex> is a title of quality, conferred by
English usage upon the younger children of earls and all the children of
viscounts and barons. The maids of honor, lords of session, and the
supreme judges of England and Ireland are entitled to the prefix. In
American usage, it is a title of courtesy merely, bestowed upon those
who hold, or have held, any of the higher public offices, esp.
governors, judges, members of Congress or of the Senate, mayors, and
often also extended to lower officials, such as city council
members.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Right honorable</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Right</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Honorableness</ent>⟦br⟧
